{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":5633,"record_hash":"sha256:7119c4f08b0709ce43a5741498bb089002011b8f00db174ba30c3fa055a07a7f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:37:16.894Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 4a8997\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 741\nOutput:\nrelationships are added later through an API or product flow, they should mean\n\"this session is relevant to this target\", not \"this session generated this\ntarget.\"\n\nGitButler's multiple-branches-in-one-worktree model is the main argument for\nturn-scoped precision. A single agent session can mostly build one feature\nbranch while a specific turn produces a bugfix that the user sends to another\nbranch. Whole-session association is therefore useful but not always precise\nenough for review sharing.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n- store sessions as the durable transcript object\n- start with derived read-time association results from capture turn evidence\n- let capture turn evidence highlight or filter the relevant part of the session\n- keep existing explicit target-to-session links as stronger evidence if they\n  already exist\n- allow future relationship metadata to carry optional turn scope if an explicit\n  API/product flow needs durable links\n\nIn other words, capture turn scope should refine a session relationship. It\nshould not move transcript ownership onto branches, changes, commits, or pull\nrequests.\n\n## Persist Or Recompute\n\nThe capture turn layer could be stored directly, or some of it could be\nrecomputed from existing records and Git state.\n\nReasons to persist capture turns:\n\n- preserves exact capture boundaries\n- preserves repository state at the time of capture\n- supports later association even after branches or worktree state changed\n- makes handoff and review timelines cheaper to query\n\nReasons to recompute some association:\n\n- avoids prematurely committing to a wrong relationship\n- keeps durable metadata smaller\n- allows better algorithms later without rewriting old data\n\nMy current take: persist the observation, not the conclusion. Store capture turn\nobjects and environment snapshots. Use them to compute association results at\nread time. Persist relationships only if an explicit API/product flow later\nneeds durable links.\n\n## Primitive Access Patterns\n\nThe model should make these reads efficient.\n\nDefine the primitive read surface independently of product UX:\n\n- `listSessions(project, filters, cursor)`: discovers sessions by recency or\n  explicit filters\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`: returns turn summaries plus\n  hydrated records for a bounded timeline window\n- `findRelatedSessions(target)`: returns scored session candidates with\n  highlighted turn keys for a branch/review/change target\n- `getRelatedSessionDetail(target, session_key, turn_window)`:\n  hydrates records around highlighted turns\n\nKeep those as read facades, not storage objects. They can evolve without\nrewriting turn metadata, and product-specific surfaces can compose them later.\n\nFor a handoff-style consumer:\n\n1. read the project session index\n2. choose a session by recency, explicit selection, or relationship\n3. read session metadata, turns, and transcript records\n4. render records grouped by turn, or choose a recent turn window\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:37:16.894Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}